1.9	We have recommended, and management has agreed to the following:
Direct the Human Resource Management Officer to assign additional staff in the Office of the Municipal Accountant who will help with the preparation of the bank reconciliation statements to improve the said Office's operational efficiency;
Direct the OIC-Municipal Accountant to immediately prepare and submit the Bank Reconciliation Statements (BRS) for all bank accounts for CY 2024 to establish the monthly adjusted bank balance;
Direct the OIC-Municipal Accountant to present the carried forward balances as reconciling items and to reconstruct these balances by utilizing available bank statements, check disbursement records, and other supporting documents and to coordinate with depository banks to obtain certified copies of past bank statements, debit/credit memos, and other pertinent records necessary to facilitate the reconstruction;
Require the OIC-Municipal Accountant to prepare a detailed bank reconciliation report that identifies and explains the causes of discrepancies in each bank account, and to submit supporting documents such as the list of outstanding checks, debit memos, and other relevant records to substantiate these discrepancies. If necessary, ensure that appropriate adjusting entries are recorded to correct any identified variances; and
Ensure that the OIC-Municipal Accountant conducts timely and monthly reconciliation of cash-in-bank accounts. The monthly BRS should be submitted to the Office of the Auditor within fifteen (15) days following the end of each month.

3.14 	We have recommended, and management has agreed to the following:
Ensure the conduct of a complete and accurate physical count of all PPE assets and ensure proper classification and documentation;
Ensure that a representative from the Commission on Audit (COA) is present during future physical inventory counts to provide proper validation and oversight;
The OIC-Municipal Accountant to update the Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Card (PPELC) and reconcile the balance against the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant, and Equipment (RPCPPE);
The General Services Officer
Maintain the Property Cards for PPEs and incorporate the balances in the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE);
Ensure all properties issued for official use by officers and employees of the municipality are covered by Property Acknowledgement Receipt (PAR). Renew Property Acknowledgment Receipts (PARs) every three years to ensure accountability.
Ensure all equipment/property is assigned with Inventory Tags/Stickers. The property sticker shall contain all vital information of each property/equipment for easy identification such as a brief description of the property/equipment; model number; serial number; property number; acquisition date; and to whom assigned/responsible Officer/Employee;
The Inventory Committee
Prepare annual Report on the Physical Count of Semi-Expendable Property (RPCSP) for Property, Plant, and Equipment (PPE) items with a cost below the capitalization threshold of ₱50,000;
Prepare a Report on the Physical Count of Inventories and submit it to the concerned COA Auditor no later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively;
Conduct a one-time cleansing of PPE accounts following the guidelines and procedures on inventory taking, recognition of those found at the station, and disposition for non-existing/missing PPE prescribed in COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020, to establish PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition, and accountability; and
Initiate the disposal of unserviceable PPEs once they meet the conditions for disposal as outlined in Item B of Part II of the Revised Manual on the Disposal of Government Properties under COA-DBM Joint Circular No. 2024-1, dated January 30, 2024. Systematic and timely disposal proceedings are essential to avoid further deterioration of the properties and consequent depreciation in their value.

We have recommended, and management has agreed to the following:
Require employees directly responsible for the delayed GSIS remittance to refund the improperly charged amount of ₱12,714.88 from government funds to avoid audit disallowance;
Implement internal controls and procedures to guarantee the timely remittance of all GSIS obligations, including premium contributions, loan amortizations, interest, and other dues; and
Ensure prompt and timely remittance of GSIS premium contributions and loan amortizations within the specified period to avoid incurring interest charges and further penalties;

We have recommended, and the management, agreed to the following:
Direct the Municipal Treasurer to enforce monitoring of remittances by requiring the collecting officers to remit daily or regularly and in full the amounts received and collected. However, when collections are minimal and daily remittance becomes costly and impractical, he shall require remittance or deposit at least once a week, or as soon as the collections reach ₱10,000.00, pursuant to Section 69(1) of PD 1445 and Item 32, Chapter II of the Revised Cash Examination Manual;
Direct the Liquidating Officer to maintain close monitoring of the remittances made by collecting officers, ensuring that Reports of Collections and Deposits (RCDs) are submitted on a daily or regular basis. As such, review the accountable forms actually submitted during remittances and reconcile them with the reported issuances and remaining balances reflected in the collectors’ RCDs to verify the accuracy and completeness of collections;
Direct the Liquidating Officer to prepare a consolidated Report of Collections and Deposits (RCD) that summarizes both the collections turned over to her by the collecting officers and her own collections, ensuring accurate reporting, proper documentation, and strengthened accountability over government funds;
Require all accountable officers to update their cashbooks daily or immediately upon receipt of collections. Ensure that transactions are recorded accurately, with the balance reconciled against actual cash on hand to strengthen internal controls and prevent discrepancies.

We have recommended to the BAC Chairman and BAC Secretariat the following:
Immediately submit to the Office of the Auditor the contracts and all supporting documents for the abovementioned infrastructure projects and goods;
Ensure strict compliance with COA Circular No. 2009-001 by submitting perfected contracts and their supporting documents within five (5) working days from execution for all future procurements;
Coordinate with the Engineering Office to submit the lacking supporting documents for the Concreting of 100 lm Barangay Road, Calipapa, SND, to facilitate a complete and proper audit review; and
Establish a monitoring system that ensures compliance with submission deadlines and assigns accountability to specific personnel, preferably the BAC Secretariat, who has custody of procurement documents.

1.12	We recommended to the management the following:
Ensure the conduct of complete physical inventory taking. The inventory-taking shall be witnessed by any representative of the Commission on Audit;
The OIC-Municipal Accountant to update the Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Card (PPELC) and reconcile the balance against the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE);
The General Services Officer
Maintain the Property Cards for PPEs and incorporate the balances in the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE);
Ensure all properties issued for official use of officers and employees of the municipality are covered by Property Acknowledgement Receipt (PAR). Also, the GSO is to ensure all equipment/property is assigned with Inventory Tags/Stickers. The property sticker shall contain all vital information of each property/equipment for easy identification such as: brief description of the property/equipment; model number; serial number; property number; acquisition date; and to whom assigned/responsible Officer/Employee;
Identify unserviceable properties and prepare an Inspection and Inventory Report for disposal; and
The Inventory Committee to conduct one-time cleansing of PPE accounts following the guidelines and procedures on inventory taking, recognition of those found at the station, and disposition for non-existing/missing PPE prescribed in COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 in order to establish PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability.

We recommended the following:

Ensure conduct of complete physical inventory taking;

Create an Inventory Committee to be headed by the General Services Officer, and include in the committee the Municipal Engineer, Municipal Accountant, and all concerned department heads, or any representative of the said department heads. The inventory taking shall be witnessed by any representative of the Commission on Audit;

Direct the General Services Officer to maintain the Stock Cards for inventories and the Property Cards for PPEs and incorporate the balances in the Report on the Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI) and Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE);

Direct the OIC-Municipal Accountant to update the Supplies Ledger Card (SLC) and Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Card (PPELC) and reconcile the balance against the Report on the Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI) and Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE);

Direct the General Service Officer to ensure all semi-expendable equipment and properties issued for official use of officers and employees of the municipality are covered by Inventory Custodian Slip (ICS) and Property Acknowledgement Receipt (PAR), respectively. Also, the GSO is to ensure all equipment/property are assigned with Inventory Tags/Stickers. The property sticker shall contain all vital information of each property/equipment for easy identification such as: brief description of the property/equipment; model number; serial number; property number; acquisition date; and to whom assigned/responsible Officer/Employee;

Direct the General Services Officer to identify unserviceable properties and prepare an Inspection and Inventory Report for disposal; and

Conduct one-time cleansing of PPE accounts following the guidelines and procedures on inventory taking, recognition of those found at the station, and disposition for non-existing/missing PPE prescribed in COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 in order to establish PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability.

We have recommended to the Local Chief Executive the following:

Direct the HRMO and other concerned personnel to exert more effort in giving priority to hiring a licensed Certified Public Accountant as Municipal Accountant;

Direct the Municipal Accountant Designate to harness or develop her competency or efficiency by attending seminars and trainings.

We have recommended to the Local Chief Executive to:

Direct the General Services Officer to submit a Monthly Report of Fuel Consumption of construction and heavy equipment; strictly comply with the provisions of the Manual on Audit of Fuel Consumption of Government Motor Vehicles as prescribed under COA Circular No. 77-61 to be properly guided in the documentation of fuel consumption and the use of government vehicles/equipment as well as to be able to regulate fuel consumption;

Direct the OIC-Municipal Accountant-Designate to ensure that payments for fuel expenses are duly supported with duly filled up driver’s trip tickets, charge slips, and billing statements for proper evaluation of the propriety and reasonableness of fuel consumption before recording the same in the books of account;

Require the heavy equipment operators to present a duly accomplished Driver’s Trip Ticket before the use of the said equipment; 

Direct the Municipal Engineer to ensure the Approved Program of Works and Detailed Cost Estimates are readily available to support every request of fuel and to ensure that actual fuel consumption of construction and heavy equipment does not exceed the approved quantity of fuel estimated to be used in the project.

We have recommended to the Local Chief Executive the following: 
a.	Direct both the General Services Officer and the OIC Municipal Accountant to maintain Stock Cards for inventories and the Property Cards for PPEs and subsidiary ledger cards for each property, plant and equipment respectively;

b.	Require the General Services Officer to identify unserviceable properties and prepare an Inspection and Inventory Report for disposal;

c.	Direct the OIC Municipal Accountant: 

•	To update the Supplies Ledger Card (SLC) and Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Card (PPELC); and

•	Prepare necessary adjustments on the deficiencies noted in the course of the inventory taking and make reconciliation with inventory report, stock cards and subsidiary ledgers.

We have recommended the following to the Local Chief Executive:

Direct the GSO to prepare and submit the Report of the Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI), Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE), and Inventory on Local Road Networks for CY 2018;

Create an appraisal/inventory committee to conduct physical inventory taking of all properties, plant and equipment to be headed by the General Services Officer;

Direct the General Services Officer to prepare and maintain an updated Stock Cards for inventories and Property Cards for property, plant and equipment;

Direct the Municipal Accountant Designate to prepare and maintain an updated Supplies Ledger Cards;  Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Card; and Real Property Ledger Cards;

Direct the Municipal Accountant and the General Services Officer to periodic reconciliation their records;

Direct the Municipal Accountant Designate to provide residual value in computing the depreciation and the fully depreciated property account should be separated on the corresponding property account; and

Direct the General Services Officer to update the list of properties that needs to be insured and submit the list to the GSIS to be covered by insurance in order to protect the interest of the government. For lost, damaged properties without covering insurance, the liability therefore should devolve upon the parties responsible.

We have recommended the following to the Local Chief Executive:

Request the Sangguniang Bayan to enact an Ordinance to Implement and Support the Ecological Solid Waste Management Act of 2000;

Intensify campaigns which should be collaborated with the barangay officials concerned;

Enforce a continued and stricter implementation of waste segregation, and thorough collection of waste based on set schedules; and

Provide budget for the purchase of sanitary landfill.

We have recommended to the Local Chief Executive to direct the Municipal Treasurer and Revenue Collectors the following:
Adhere strictly with the rules and regulation in the handling of Accountable Forms; 
Ensure the effective performance of their functions; 
Submit the monthly Report of Accountability for Accountable Forms; and
 Turnover the used and issued Accountable Forms to the Custodian of Accountable Forms.

We have recommended the following to the Local Chief Executive:
Direct the GSO to prepare and submit the Report of the Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI), Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE), and Inventory on Local Road Networks for CY 2018;
Create an appraisal/inventory committee to conduct physical inventory taking of all properties, plant and equipment to be headed by the General Services Officer;
Direct the General Services Officer to prepare and maintain an updated Stock Cards for inventories and Property Cards for property, plant and equipment;
Direct the Municipal Accountant Designate to prepare and maintain an updated Supplies Ledger Cards;   Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Card; and Real Property Ledger Cards;
Direct the Municipal Accountant and the General Services Officer to periodic reconciliation their records;
Direct the Municipal Accountant Designate to provide residual value in computing the depreciation and the fully depreciated property account should be separated on the corresponding property account; and
Direct the General Services Officer to update the list of properties that needs to be insured and submit the list to the GSIS to be covered by insurance in order to protect the interest of the government. For lost, damaged properties without covering insurance, the liability therefore should devolve upon the parties responsible.

We have recommended to the management the following measures:

Creation of the Municipal Solid Waste Management Board in accordance with the provision of law, if there is none;

The plan should be prepared, reviewed and updated as required by law to ensure its sustainability, relevance and effectiveness;

Continued and stricter implementation of waste segregation, and thorough collection of waste based on set schedules

We have recommended to the management the following measures:
Creation of the Municipal Solid Waste Management Board in accordance with the provision of law, if there is none;
The plan should be prepared, reviewed and updated as required by law to ensure its sustainability, relevance and effectiveness;
Continued and stricter implementation of waste segregation, and thorough collection of waste based on set schedules;
The agency committed to comply with the above provision of rules and regulations. Towards this, the team shall undertake periodic monitoring.
